In wise foresight, because most of his 90 employees (inside) are in the baby boom age and the company is concerned that the project architects return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Together with the opportunity to work shortened, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer to its employees in the concept of their social program.
The civil engineers and architects thus have it easier to balance their demanding profession and child care.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of the employees (inside) of Arch.Design and with the support of the management, they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The company mini kindergarten is financed by the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from the European Social Fund and from the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this financing (grants of 2, 8 million CZK) the necessary facilities and equipment could be procured and for a period of 2 years for qualified personnel and operation are provided.
After the use of the subsidies (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue to operate the mini kindergarten for 3 more years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a full year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the settlement of applications.
The children are cared for by all-day qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age-related restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at the same time, but the day over several children alternate with each other.
The kindergarten operation is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in relation to the use of the kindergarten - without regard to the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is individual education and nursing, the program content in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the supporting program of preschool education.
The children not only play here, above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to preschool lessons, by the way they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a calculator available to the children.
What more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
The parents can take a look at the children at any time and so the stress when picking up the children late from a distant kindergarten is eliminated.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also emerging here.
Arch.Design thus joined the Czech companies, which offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and encourage their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house still fascinates even after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló by the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic shapes was nicknamed "bone house".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile shards and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of sheds and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features for the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The façade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures that are reminiscent of nature and living things.
Only on closer inspection do you notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and well-thought-out order.
At night, the whole façade looks even more plastic, more dramatic and the special illumination reinforces the shine of the colors.
The same sweeping lines and intricate shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-like shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and groins.
The Haus Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia Nr. 43 was created by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, which architect Emilio Sala Cortese carried out.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to the idea of Gaudí's idea for an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
However, the apartment building Casa Batlló did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
Especially on its drawing board, the decorations for the representative apartment of the reality owner were created and also the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other sculptors and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí’s Casa Milá house in the Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was nicknamed "bone house" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms because of its house.
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "yawning house."
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a central heating system, unique for the time, with venting channels and typical fireplaces for the house.
A little bizarre, her 45-degree inclination already seems.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building codes at the time and was by no means deceived by them.
Before the start of construction, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he made about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so horrified by the result two years later that they demanded a remedy.
The councillors also came across the fact that the building with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no changes, quite the opposite - only fifteen days after the district's request in this regard, Josep Batlló submitted an application to approve the rental of the two highest floors in the house - and it was promptly granted to it.
The homeowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery in 2. Floor was a social salon, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building passes through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the conversion, all right angles and straight lines were eliminated and replaced by curved and curved walls.
But Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could chat comfortably without having to give up a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new façade, the house also received a rather unusual roof and two other floors due to Gaudí's conversion.
Also impressive is Gaudí's play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is clad and the lighthouses.
The play of these two colors gives all the floors of the house a maximum of light.
In doing so, he simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors, which, on the contrary, absorb sunlight.
The house Casa Batlló, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can visit anyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is open to the public.
The homeowners decided only in the year to this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this is a quite profitable business, the visits were maintained, and they were also extended to other common and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard stem, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes get a 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, you should try to make friends with one of the house residents and visit him at home.
