More and more parents want human monitoring devices to have the kids under control
The fear for their own children is growing and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system, which was originally invented for the search for cars, can just as well locate people, which would also be helpful in such cases, as recently as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette box, but soon it should not be bigger than a wristwatch.
Many people have terrified the case of the disappeared Anička and so they are looking for ways to better protect their children.
Also for the price of an impairment of their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is by no means about spying, but about an effective means of reducing the likelihood of tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices on the Czech market.
“I admit that there may be misuse of such devices in individual cases, for example, if you put it in someone’s pocket without him knowing about it, but we have not had such a case to record so far.”
