A longer index finger as a ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at less risk of developing prostate cancer.
That's the surprising result of a study published Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is said to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, and this especially in men up to sixty," explained the study's co-author, Ros Eeles, a professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if genetic risks or other risk factors are present, such as family health burdens, Ms. Eeles added.
In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but at the same time 3000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the same likelihood of prostate cancer applied as to 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were of the same length.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, for men up to sixty even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which already forms in prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone is equivalent to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone in particular accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, leading Czech geneticist and former chairwoman of the Academy of Sciences, told ČTK that he was fleetingly aware of this study, but that he did not consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk to be "completely proven" so far.
