American soldiers have a new "smart weapon."
American troops have used a new "smart" weapon in Afghanistan for the first time, previously known only by their code designation XM-25.
The generals hope that this new automatic weapon will influence the conflict with the Taliban there and shift the balance of power in their favor.
The new weapon is something like a super-accurate cannon.
Their projectiles are steered to the finish by laser with a accuracy of only a few meters.
The special projectiles of caliber 25 mm, which are designed for this rifle and contain highly explosives, work practically like small grenades.
The projectiles can be programmed to explode not only on impact with the target but at any point of their ballistic trajectory.
That is, you can use them against an enemy who is hiding behind an obstacle - a wall or in the trench.
For it is usually not protected from above, so the murderous steel splinter rain from above can easily put it out of action.
According to Richard Audett, who participated in the development of the XM-25, the new combat rifle is the first infantry weapon to take advantage of "smart" technologies.
“The soldier basically proceeds like this: he targets the target and sends out a laser beam that determines the distance, so he gains an exact visor point, after which he corrects the elevation angle, then he only needs to push it off.
“Let’s say they measured 543 m.”
“When you push off, the gun charges up and shoots the projectile to the distance 543 meters plus minus one, two or three meters.
