The Japanese group Fujitsu is relocating its branch in Bad Homburg to Frankfurt.
As the industry giant, which specializes in computers and its maintenance, announced on Wednesday, 400 women and men will move their workplace from the previous office building at Marienbader Platz in Bad Homburg to the Astro Park in July next year, which is a large office complex on Lyoner Straße in the Niederrad district of Frankfurt.
A spokeswoman for Fujitsu explained that in the medium term, a further 100 jobs of the Group should be accommodated there, which were previously distributed among the region.
The rental offer was extremely attractive, in addition, the open-plan offices in Astro Park would better accommodate the way employees work.
In Bad Homburg, too, Fujitsu had been merely a tenant.
The responsible managing director Bernd Wagner said, "with Frankfurt-Niederrad we have found a central location with excellent infrastructure".
The excellent connection to the airport is particularly important for a global company like Fujitsu.
The new move of an important company within the region yesterday evoked joy among the winners and disappointment among the losers.
Frankfurt Economic Affairs Director Markus Frank (CDU) said that a "global player" had been won again.
This is a "great confession to the location."
Fujitsu fits the city, the settlement is an important impulse for Niederrad.
