Amazon suspends server - threats against Assange
WikiLeaks is becoming increasingly distressed.
The Internet service provider Amazon has banned the disclosure platform from its servers.
There may be political pressure behind it after the publication of hundreds of thousands of secret diplomatic cables.
WikiLeaks founder Assange is reportedly in England.
The WikiLeaks disclosure platform is coming under increasing fire in the United States.
The internet activists lost access to their previous American server and are now looking for an internet home in Europe.
The prominent American Senator Joe Lieberman, meanwhile, called on other countries and companies to boycott WikiLeaks.
And WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange, who is on Interpol's manhunt lists, is said to be in the UK, according to a newspaper report.
"Wikileaks of Amazon servers supplanted."
"Free speech in the land of the free," the revelation activists said via short message service Twitter on Wednesday (local time).
Shortly before, the Internet company Amazon had banned the WikiLeaks documents from its servers.
The Internet activists had resorted to the Amazon Web Service (AWS) when publishing the secret diplomatic cables in order to be able to cope with the high access figures to the documents.
WikiLeaks said: “Great – our dollars are now being spent to employ people in Europe.”
If Amazon has such a problem with freedom of speech, "they should stop selling books."
Amazon stopped the use of its servers by WikiLeaks after employees of Senator Joe Lieberman had done investigations, the television channel CNN reported, citing the office of Liebermans.
The chairman of the Senate Homeland Security Committee had threatened Amazon with a boycott, the British "Guardian" reported.
"I would have liked Amazon to take this action earlier in light of the previous releases of classified information by WikiLeaks," the senator said.
Lieberman, meanwhile, called for the platform to be denied use of servers in other countries.
"WikiLeaks' illegal, outrageous and reckless approach puts our national security at risk and endangers lives around the globe," the statement said.
“No responsible company – whether American or foreign – should help WikiLeaks in its efforts to disseminate stolen material.”
WikiLeaks founder Assange, who is wanted by authorities in Sweden on suspicion of rape, is on Interpol's manhunt list.
According to a report by the London newspaper The Independent, the 39-year-old Australian is staying in the UK, the exact location is known to Scotland Yard.
The internet activist has always described the investigation in Sweden as intrigue of his opponents.
WikiLeaks spokesman Kristinn Hrafnsson said in London there had been threats.
“There were even calls for a murder of Julian Assange.”
That's why Assange rightly fears for his safety, Hrafnsson said.
The WikiLeaks founder will therefore continue to hide.
Hrafnsson was obviously responding to statements from North America.
In America, former Arkansas Republican Governor Mike Huckabee had demanded that the person in charge of the WikiLeaks revelations be charged with treason and executed.
In Canada, an adviser to Prime Minister Stephen Harper - apparently ironically - said on television Assange should be "killed" and Obama could "use a drone."
Meanwhile, an exchange of blows broke out between the White House and Assange.
American President Barack Obama's spokesman, Robert Gibbs, called it "ridiculous and absurd" that Assange had called for Secretary of State Hillary Clinton's resignation in case she is responsible for recently revealed spying calls to diplomats.
“I’m not entirely sure why we care about a guy’s opinion with a website,” Gibbs said.
“Our foreign policy and the interests of this country are far more significant than its one website.”
The U.S. government is now putting the protection of its databases to the test.
The Vice-Director of the Center for Counter-Terrorism Measures, Russell Travers, had been appointed as special representative, the White House said.
Travers was responsible for developing "necessary structural reforms" that became necessary after the disclosure of the embassy reports by WikiLeaks.
The White House also wants to review ways the entire administration exchanges and protects information.
The U.S. government also announced that it would provide for the safety of dissidents and activists if they were put in danger through the WikiLeaks publication.
"We have made every effort to get in touch with them," foreign ministry spokesman Philip Crowley said.
“We stand ready to protect them if that become necessary.”
The Ice University
At the "Gelato University" near Bologna, ice cream confectioners are prepared for better seasons.
The three-day basic course for future gelatieri has the largest inflow and visitors from all over the world.
Where does all the ice come from?
From the gelatier and from the gelataio.
The gelatier, in German somewhat ancient the ice cream confectioner, produces the cream according to all the rules of Italian ice cream making.
The Gelataio takes the ice cream from the fridge with a spatula, spreads it into the waffle and then sells it.
To know this, you don’t have to go to Anzola dell’Emilia in the province of Bologna.
But if you want to know more about ice, you can't get past the "Gelato-University" of the Italian company Carpigiani.
The Ice University established the manufacturer of ice machines in 2003 to ensure that the ice cream from its machines can meet the high Italian ideals everywhere.
The three-day basic course for future gelatieri has the largest inflow and visitors from all over the world.
But there are also multi-day special courses around chocolate ice cream and internships in the in-house ice cream parlor.
Some dream of a new career in the midlife crisis, others just venture on the smooth ice of their vague longings.
This time there are 40 participants from 19 countries from all continents - from Brazil to Hungary to Saudi Arabia.
Jacky, an art teacher from California, loves the slow food movement and wants to offer a European quality product in the country of industrial ice cream in the future.
Anke from Berlin is a management consultant and wants to bag something of his own after years in a nerve-racking job.
Two young Egyptian women dream of opening an ice cream parlor in Cairo.
A man from Malta and one from Brazil want to improve the quality of the ice cream in their bars - and Canadian housewife Julia comes in because her children love Italian ice cream.
Maestro-Gelatier Luciano Ferrari first explains to the participants the ideal properties of the perfect ice cream.
The decisive factor is not only good taste, but also the silky suppleness and the good consistency.
In his training, Luciano does not forget the icing on the one of the national and southern superstructure: "Italian gelato is simply the best - and then there is still a lot of romance."
The first step to manufacturing seems quite simple.
Luciano dumps the basic ingredients milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large mixing device that heats everything to 85 degrees with an electronic program and then immediately cools to four degrees.
Then he turns up a tap on the machine, and out comes a pasteurized white base cream, basis for all milk ice creams.
Immediately, the lecturer is assayed with questions: Can ice cream only be produced with natural substances without a stabilizer?
How can you give free rein to your own experimentation?
Luciano warns against being led astray by the zeitgeist.
If you talk about ice cream "only from natural ingredients", you may still have used stabilizers - usually a natural product, such as guar flour from the guar bean.
Of course, you can also make ice cream without a stabilizer, only it must be sold within a day, otherwise it will collapse, and the customer bites on loud ice granules.
Certain variations on the base mass are permitted.
It becomes more exciting with the aromas.
For the taste in the ice cream, Maestro Luciano distinguishes between the ingredients you buy in the fruit section or in the sweets of the supermarket.
There are also powders and pastes.
“The suppliers will all try to turn on you dozens of flavored additives.”
“But you should just experiment.”
Either with the fruit sorbets with sugar and fresh fruit.
Or just with the ice cream from the white base, which becomes a yellow cream with eggs and with cocoa powder as the basis for all possible chocolate seductions.
Now the students are allowed to go to the ice machines.
Luciano lets them produce four different types of vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut ice cream each - with or without eggs in the base, with more or less vanilla aroma or other natural additives.
The fruit ice varieties are also subjected to the same experiment.
More flavorings, more fruit puree - this is not necessarily better in terms of taste.
Hazelnut ice cream doesn't necessarily taste nuttier if it contains more hazelnuts.
The most popular kiwi ice cream is made by the working group, which uses more fruit, less water and slightly less stabilizer.
Only a balanced mixture raises the taste of a gelato correctly, says Luciano.
Ice production is a calculation task: If peach puree is used with a lot of sugar, the sugar content must be reduced in the basic recipe.
For lemon ice cream, an extra portion of sugar is required.
Luciano pulls out a device with which it determines the sugar content of the fruit varieties (winemakers measure the Oechsle in the grape must).
Fortunately, tables make it easier to calculator.
Making ice cream no longer requires as much physical effort as it used to.
Not only the device for the automatic production of the base material helps.
There is also a device in which the finished ice mixture is simultaneously beaten until creamy and cooled to minus temperatures.
Despite all automation, small breakdowns are not missing.
The Brazilian Gustavo licks himself and his course colleagues from top to bottom with fruit puree when the oversized hand blender gets out of control.
"In every course," says Maestro Luciano, "it's only a matter of time before something like this happens."
Controllers in the twilight
The European food authority Efsa is subverted by the industry experimenting with genetic plants.
This accusation is now formulated by the expert group Testbiotech, which sees itself as an independent institute for the impact assessment of biotechnology.
"It sounds like a conspiracy theory, but we documented it well," Testbiotech chief executive Christoph Then told reporters in Munich on Wednesday.
The head of the Efsa expert group on genetically modified plants, Harry Kuiper, and another Efsa expert have also been under contract with the lobbyist association Ilsi for years.
It is paid for by corporations such as Monsanto, Nestle or Bayer.
Kuiper has played a major role in the Efsa testing regulations for genetically produced plants and is thus in a clear conflict of interest, criticizes Then.
The Efsa regulations are identical in paragraphs with position papers of the Ilsi and thus bear the signature of the industry, which is actually to be controlled by the authority in the Italian Parma.
This is the second time that Testbiotech has criticized a conflict of interest.
For example, a high-ranking Efsa manager has recently been without conditions or transitional period to the Swiss agricultural group Syngenta - and has thus changed sides.
The Mitteldeutscher Rundfunk (MDR) had also recently revealed personnel links between the controlling EU authority and the industrial lobby, which the Federal Environment Agency, as well as EU parliamentarians, have made noisy.
Efsa, however, cannot identify a conflict of interest.
We use all serious data, including those of industry, as long as they are of high professional quality, according to a statement.
The experts who work for Efsa do not require that they have no contacts with the industry.
You would have to disclose these, though.
Kuiper is conceding his work for the International Life Sciences Institute (Ilsi) in the United States.
This describes itself as a neutral forum for experts from science, industry and politics - among other things, for the risk assessment for biotechnology without a lobbying assignment.
In the matter, independent experts such as Then criticize that genetically modified plants are currently approved without any feeding test in animals and that the reaction of gene plants to environmental influences is not being tested.
"We want to know what, for example, genetically modified corn is doing on the field," says Then.
Current practice is to only test isolated proteins, but not the whole gene plant, which does not provide reliable results.
"If you don't look for the risks, how are you supposed to find them?" Then asks accusingly.
Angelika Hilbeck thinks so, too.
The scientist has been researching genetic engineering since 1994 and is currently working at the Technical University of Zurich.
In this field, as in the USA, industry is now increasingly trying to influence or discredit critical scientists.
There are therefore hardly any researchers who are not intertwined with corporations.
For companies critical studies are usually not published.
"The industry controls security research," Hilbeck asserts.
