Obama halts new oil drilling
There will be no new oil drilling off the coast of Florida in the Gulf of Mexico in the coming years.
A corresponding ban has been issued by the government in Washington - and thus finally revoked its previous plans.
Even off the Atlantic coast, new drilling remains prohibited for the time being.
This was announced by Interior Minister Ken Salazar on Wednesday.
The trigger for the strict ban, which is to apply for at least the next five years, is the explosion of the drilling platform "Deepwater Horizon" in April.
Before the disaster, which killed eleven workers and led to the biggest environmental disaster in the U.S., President Barack Obama, under pressure from the opposition and industry, had signaled his willingness to allow new drilling in the eastern part of the Gulf of Mexico.
The supporters want to reduce the dependence of the United States on oil supplies from abroad.
Anyone responsible for the devastating oil spill in the Gulf has not yet been conclusively clarified.
At the heart of the criticism is the British energy company BP, which is facing billions in demands.
A commission of inquiry on behalf of Obama is due to present its findings in the course of December.
In October, Interior Minister Ken Salazar lifted the drilling stop imposed after the explosion.
