The Democative Routine
The democracy movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, just like the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil's influence is greater than that of the United States.
These were the findings of the Latinobarómetro survey, which was conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly striking in this year's September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and second, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (s. Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has been around approx. 6% grows, the number of democracy advocates increased from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Even in Mexico, where the economy has been recovering since last year's sharp slump, such a trend can be seen.
Yet only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region's most populous countries, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (s. Diagram 2).
Ca. 44% of respondents said they are satisfied with their country's democratic practice. This is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Diagram 3).
About 34% trust their country's Congress and 45% of their government. Both figures correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and previous years, respectively). 24%).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined efforts for more democracy.
That this continued even during the Great Depression may be because Latin America's countries experienced only a brief period of recession and recovered quickly.
Moreover, the poor were caught by a stronger social network.
(According to reports by the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and has fallen again by 32% this year.)
Yet from country to country there are strong differences in mood (s. Diagram 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread thinking of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
Only for the second time since the beginning of the survey, many respondents in Latin America see a bigger problem in crime in their country than in unemployment (s. diagram 5).
Ca. 31% say that either they themselves or a family member have been victims of a crime in the last year. However, compared to 38% last year, the figures have fallen, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
The increasing economic performance is reflected in the stronger support of the private and market economy: approx. 71% of respondents nationally stated that the private sector is essential for development, compared to 56% in 2007 (s. Diagram 6).
Ca. 58% said that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are in favor of a private sector), although their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, nationalized many private companies.
Brazil has the largest weight in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared with 11% last year).
The respondents in Mexico and most countries in Central America, on the other hand, see the most influential country in the US, with this role being assumed by Venezuela in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
