Secretly in the middle
In the weeks after the sudden death of your husband, Argentina's president, Cristina Fernández, experienced a wave of sympathy that pushed up her popularity rate by 20 points to over 50%. That's the highest figure since her election in 2007.
Whether this will help her to re-elect next year, however, depends on whether the visibly grieving Cristina Fernández is more willing to compromise than her late husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs for this are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who also steered economic policy after his wife's election, frequently drew up budget plans that did not fully take tax revenues, economic growth and inflation into account.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the extra revenues at their own discretion.
On paper, the Fernández administration lost a majority in Congress last year.
Yet the opposition is divided and Kirchner's death after a heart attack on 27. October led to further rifts.
Some regime critics from the ranks of the ruling peronists stood behind Cristina Fernández.
Yet after chaotic sessions (at which one parliamentarian punched another in the face and others accused the government of bribery) Congress failed to pass the budget for 2011.
"I'm not going to discuss it," the president said.
The 2010 budget now also applies to next year, giving the president even more opportunity to spend money at her own discretion.
The economy is running hot: it is likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently at 11.1%, yet numerous private estimates - and wage demands of the unions - are driving the value to almost 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina was shaken by economic crises, declared growth and poverty reduction to be its main goals, rather than the inflation cut.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, bullying the private sector and purging the National Institute for Statistics and Census INDEC, which subsequently garnished the official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández take a more moderate path now?
She has called on the private sector and the union leaders to hold talks.
And according to official statements, wage increases are to be limited to 18% next year.
The high world market prices for Argentina's agricultural products have given the economy a strong boost.
Yet inflation undermined the growth spurt by a major devaluation in 2002.
For this reason, Cristina Fernández may want to reconnect Argentina financially to the rest of the world.
Earlier this year, the government reached an agreement with securities holders who had rejected the country's previous debt restructuring in 2001.
Now Fernández seems to be pushing for a deal with the donors from the Paris Club, to whom she ca. $6.7 billion owes.
The Kirchners had always rejected a review by the IMF, as is customary elsewhere.
