Arsenic-resistant microbe could allow for new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of an alien bacterial species, which can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, it is, in their view, a sign that a life is possible even without the elements previously considered vital.
“This organism has two options.”
“He needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow.”
"That makes it very special, even though it's almost a kind of 'foreign' life form," Paul C.W explained. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as the scientists found, the bacterium in California's Mono Lake grows even further when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
"You wonder what else is possible," said the co-author of the report Ariel D. Anbar from Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, according to Anbar.
The study looks at microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details of the discovery were announced gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of alien life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary systems organisms can initiate biochemical processes with the help of other elements and that the 'standard elements' that, in our opinion, are absolutely vital, are not necessarily fixed," explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute of the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty, because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose the mono lake due to the high arsenic content.
Because arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she assumed that microbes exposed to both may be able to replace one element with the other.
“The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to the fact that it behaves chemically similar to phosphorus.”
“This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from the other.”
“But the difference is so great that arsenic works differently than phosphorus. It enters our biochemical system, where it smears virtually everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic. It adapted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, the fact that it can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon, on which arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a lecturer in microbiology at the University of Florida, is not new to the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic. But so far, there hasn't been a working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, that's why science has assumed that early life forms used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than it did in the early Earth Ages," according to Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research work was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
