The deal was announced in a joint statement after a meeting of Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton with Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov in an additional article in the security summit.
The U.S. government had spent years trying to convince Belarus to not collect highly enriched uranium and appeared to have reached a hurdle last spring.
Yet officials from the U.S. government told The Washington Post that two secret agreements with Belarus have been made in the past two months to remove 187 pounds of weapons-grade uranium from a Belarusian research facility.
That set the stage for Wednesday's agreement to remove the rest of the material - about £500, according to an official employee who remains anonymous due to the issue's sensitivity.
The agreement appears to be one of the key findings of Obama's "nuclear security summit of the 47 nations" from April, which had ruled out Belarus.
And it was obviously good enough to secure the former Soviet republic's invitation to the next summit in 2012.
“I was really excited by the fact that they want a seat in the Nuclear Security Summit (of 2012).”
"This proves to me that it works," said Ken Luongo, president of the Global Security Partnership, a group to promote nuclear security.
Clinton called the agreement "a very significant, important step" by Belarus.
Obama promised in April 2009 in Prague to secure all precarious nuclear material within four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries get rid of their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will be the seventh.
A dozen countries did it under the George W government. Bush.
At the time of Obama's nuclear safety summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko has declared that the nation will never give up its uranium.
"How to retain highly enriched uranium - hundreds of kilos, which is fundamentally weapons-grade, and less enriched uranium," Lukashenko said at the time.
“This is our raw material... We’re not going to make dirty bombs out of it and we’re not going to sell it to anyone.”
“We use it exclusively for research purposes, that’s all.”
Belarus nevertheless approached the US a few months ago when it indicated interest in the meeting of a deal.
The first attempt to remove the uranium of Belarus in October was particularly complicated because the material was slightly irradiated, officials say.
It was loaded into a special train that was more than 1,300 miles to a Russian factory for storage and disposal for, officials say.
The second attempt was decided on Monday and was carried out by plane, according to the officials.
The U.S. government is paying $14 million for this effort, with much of the money going into Belarusian research with weakly enriched uranium that cannot be used for nuclear weapons.
"This was extremely carefully coordinated and coordinated to build trust," which led to the agreement signed by Clinton, said Andrew Bieniawski, a representative of the Department of Energy working on global risk reduction.
The James Martin Centre for Non-Proliferable Studies estimates that Belarus has had at least 88 pounds of weapons-grade uranium this year, as well as hundreds of pounds of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus wants to dissolve its camp by 2012, according to the joint agreement.
Relations between Belarus and the US have been strained for years, primarily because of Lukashenko's harsh disregard for human rights.
But Wednesday's statement suggests a possible rapprochement.
“Welcoming the progress of these global security issues, the United States of America and Belarus announces that increased respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remains a central issue in improving bilateral relations and it is essential to the progress of the country and its citizens,” she explains.
No objections from the Spanish government against CIA flights
The Spanish government had no objections to the CIA flights with Taliban and Al Qaeda prisoners across Spanish territory to Guantánamo, according to a telegram from the U.S. ambassador to Madrid.
This is reflected in the documents enveloped by WikiLeaks and forwarded to the daily newspaper "El País" (by cable). It is added that former Deputy Prime Minister María Teresa Fernández de la Vega called for the Spanish government to be informed "to demonstrate that foreign aircraft flying over Spain will be adequately monitored."
In June 2006, following the publication of a report by the Council of Europe indicting aid to human rights-contempt practices in a dozen countries, including Spain, former North American Ambassador Eduardo Aguirre and Fernández de la Vega discussed.
