Red Bull wins in F1 with a secret weapon from Siemens
The cars are improved with software in real time.
Since the 2004 Red Bull invaded the world of Formula One, their history in this exquisite universe of speed has been marked by surprises and successes.
Initially, no one paid attention to the newcomer and despite his steeply rising career during the last seasons, everyone relied on the victory of the Ferrari of Fernando Alonso at the final sprint last November.
Without wanting to reduce the skills of the German driver and world champion Sebastian Vettel or the power of Renault's engine, the "secret weapon" that the Multi Siemens Red Bull put in the hands, and thus created a winning team, has become a legend.
In reality, it is a powerful software for simulating processes that the German company launched in 2007 for purposes that are not related to car racing.
This computer science program, known as PLM, has been used for the development of assembly chains in factories around the world, energy plants and high-precision instruments.
The purpose is to provide a faithful reproduction or Simulation of a product or process before it is actually built to avoid errors and unnecessary costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon's cameras, Sukhoi's aircraft and Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that with the use of this software in the Formula 1 factory Red Bull "in a few hours, almost in real time," the changes and improvements detected at the races and in the tests can design and execute.
Russwurm explains that in 1992, an average of ten technicians worked in the racing stables, who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements in a season.
Red Bull's team employs 180 highly qualified young people today. With powerful computer systems, they perform analyses and all possible changes to the race car.
The Siemens manager said the PLM software was able to analyze and improve all the components of Red Bull's race cars, with the exception of the engine for which Renault is solely responsible.
The materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are changed.
The changes can be transferred from the virtual reality of the simulator to reality within less than 24 hours thanks to advanced production facilities and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limit set for this crazy technical perfectionism is the $40 million that a Formula 1 team is allowed to spend on its races in a season.
Red Bull has set up its high-tech factory for the development and manufacture of its racing cars in a site 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings in which visits - especially by journalists - are severely limited.
All that happens there is Top Secret.
The workforce includes 580 people, including the two pilots, world champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
But Red Bull's true Formula 1 - hero is undoubtedly the latest world champion Sebastian Vetell.
Behind the enormous technological resources that the energy drink manufacturer puts at the services of its participation on the racetracks, hide other protagonists whose support is invaluable and whose awareness is equal to zero.
The plant's chief of technology, Steve Nevey, stresses that five years ago it was still possible to say that progress in R&D for race cars contributed 50 percent to the victory and the pilots were in charge of the rest.
Today, the share values have changed. The technology accounts for 85 percent of the success, while the contribution of pilots is estimated at 15 percent.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel and Webber can never be replaced by IT, because they "are unpredictable gladiators."
