On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adjustment measures, ranging from tax reductions for small and micro-enterprises, the regulation of temporary employment companies or the cancellation of the 426 euros of support for the unemployed who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatization of 49 percent from AENA, the management of the Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, with the help of the former Prime Minister Felipe González, supports the criticism of the Chancellor Angela Merkel as responsible, who has conjured the current crisis.
How to understand these processes?
It is anticipated that Merkel's position is not a mistake of her public relations.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefinition of the euro.
Germany is taking a fundamentally new perspective to shape our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of much of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, there are three possible ways out of the crisis in Germany.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the Deutsche Mark - although this currently sounds more like science fiction -, supported by much of the public opinion, ca. 50% of the population.
The third: a transformation of the euro according to German proposals. This means: more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of the countries that pass the requirements; possibly the payment of some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time. Therefore, there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled out of its sleeve a constitutional reform to prevent this from 2016.
That was the first sign of the drifting apart between what Germany thought necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign set the Central European country when Merkel painfully pushed out the decision to save Greece.
At the time, this was heavily criticized. But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, public and published opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, Merkel comes out again in the last days of October with a clear position. It calls for a reform of the European Union's agreements to allow the rescue of a country while requiring private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European as it advanced the Irish crisis and all of the following.
But their proposal, though somewhat sweetened, was adopted. In the coming months, we will participate in the reform of the European Union, which is to enable these measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that does not intend to cross it.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures now have to be taken - there will no longer be the old way of working of the euro from this date.
2013 will be the birth year of a new currency area in which the opposing countries can be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent and in this case the private sector must cover part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we have to take a hard growth course, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness, and positive foreign economic balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, just as it was cited by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly about not understanding it.
It's not just about cutting the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do in these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turmoil will pass into more calm.
And that we will use the opportunities that are offered to us by the spring of 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the discussion with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in her own house has prepared her way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like anything would change about that.
Among the possibilities envisaged, the fact that we would have to leave the euro area, which is full of scarce countries, cannot be ruled out.
In this case, Germany could still tell us it warned us.
Sport and environment
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to bypass a sanction.
The alleged exclusion in the match of 23, which was allegedly instigated by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) November against the Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed about whether or not it was an unsportsmanlike act and whether both players should possibly be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is generally known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will meet the prescribed sanction in the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next phase of the game without cards.
Finally, UEFA's disciplinary commission punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with varying amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It is so prevalent that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but in this sport followed rules.
Part of the debate about the presented case is due to the fact that a team from the Real Madrid football club (who, in his anthem, pretended to be noble and honor and, on other occasions, had punished his players for similar incidents) played the lead role, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added one episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this practice, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts constitute a rule circumvention. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of the sport, but seem to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused to the sportsmanship should be investigated.
The sportsman defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not jeopardized by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the infringing players from taking an unjustified benefit from the opposing team. This, too, did not happen.
The paradox of the action of the players of the Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we usually mean by false play or circumvention, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible for it to be punished by the referee.
The players waited and joyfully accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the infringers pulled out of the deliberate fouls.
Here it should be emphasized that the rival was neither put in a less favorable position nor benefits for the game played were required, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue to play with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that the players will begin the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could also retire at some point. In addition, players receive a sanction with this procedure and move into the second card cycle, in which they are eliminated less than in the first cycle because of card accumulation with a card.
With that said, it's not so clear whether it's really an advantage.
Ultimately, such approaches are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions in order to derive the greatest possible benefit from the regulations.
In this case, the players did not want to avoid a sanction (that would actually be a clear case of regular circumvention), they wanted to choose when to undergo it.
They made a strategic decision without dodging or fleeing from it.
Although the line between inventiveness and the rule environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemic was created as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the type of provoked rule transmission.
The damage done to the principles of sport through these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
