The US is changing the rules for obtaining a visa
Persons must present themselves at the consulate before their interview at the service centres for visa application; costs are thus shortened.
From the 10. January 2011, procedures for applying for a visa changed at the United States Embassy and in the consulates.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves at the visa application service centres (ASC, the initial letters in English) before their interview in the consulate.
The staff of the ASC shall take up the applicant's biometric data, which will be reviewed by the consulate prior to the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa decreases, because it is no longer necessary to pay the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed out separately.
The applicant shall only make a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the return on $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not have to have a conversation in the consulate, they only have to introduce themselves at the nearest ASC, where they present their documents and their fingerprints are taken.
Since the biometric data is obtained in the ASC, the applicants who need a second appointment for the interview in the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa in the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the $26 service surcharge.
Additional information about the new visa application procedure can be found in the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
