But if you look into the detail, things are a little more complicated.
This money, according to the Copenhagen Treaty, should be "new and additional" to ensure that an additional deployment has been brought in without being to the detriment of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the benchmark that they consider to be best.
The EU Commission, for example, has chosen itself as a benchmark for that of 2009: international financing will be maintained and will add 150 million over three years as part of the "fast-start" financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or in terms of conditions at official development assistance level.
In return, France felt the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 was "new and additional."
In other words, there are no benchmarks for the previous year's expenditure or at the global level of official development assistance.
Specifically, the total amount of French support for developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) - France pretends to comply with its commitment to the "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule about that yet, and everyone chooses their computing mode.
Some, such as France, find €1 borrowed as equivalent to €1 donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often projects tied to emissions containment) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro, which is co-opted as the equivalent for a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan for the investor country should be credited as an exposure (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing else in mind than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of €420 million by taking out 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5%) 36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself of this.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans to a large extent.
Germany is demanding 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are 100% in their commitments with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to fulfil its obligations, France gives just 10 cents and means a comparable stake.
Nice hocus-pocus!
All in all, France operates in its fast-start financing with a double hoax: in part with a further development of the action over time and partly with the reality of financial commitment.
France manages to believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" millions in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros in the process.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a doubly negative effect; once internally (why do the other member states continue with the donation, if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries do not allow to be completely deceived...
The chapter of premature financing only a small question in a relatively short time compared to the totality of discussions about the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the UNFCCC's immense machinery.
Let's hope this is not going to be the case.
However, it is essential to learn his lesson from this first year of premature financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its type of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could bring forward the discussions on the subject of the long-term financing (a different, decisive and currently discussed topic): one does not escape the question of "calculability" or the type of booking of its loans.
France could change its position to be as progressive about the issues of dispute as it is with other things.
So the hope rests on the new environment minister, Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about the fast-launch of France and its vision of "predictability" as well as the use of loans would naturally raise the international basis of trust necessary for further discussions.
Alarm - pesticides taken by children
A child of 10 years old takes 81 different chemical substances over the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Association of Générations Futures (former movement to protect the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which explains that its results "do not reflect statistically significant value in view of the small number of samples analyzed, but represent illustration character of the treated problem," had bought between July and September the foods usually consumed by a roughly ten-year-old child at meals, plus a snack in the supermarkets in Oise and Paris, between July and September.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit parts, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - have been studied, as have been checks from laboratories in search of chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is devastating: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as possibly or probably carcinogenic and five classified as safely carcienogenic, as well as 37 substances with an endocrinin disorder factor, according to studies of several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if, in the approximate totality of cases, the legal limits for each chemical, individually taken substance are not exceeded, it is nevertheless very well evident from this survey that the reality in which the consumer may be exposed to carcinogenic substances or substances with an endocrinin disturbing factor is worrying," the association observes.
Already at breakfast, the butter and tea with milk alone contain more than ten of the possibly cancer-causing residues and three safely proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the study, shows traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, included in lunch, where the study has found traces of an insecticide strictly banned in the EU.
Furthermore, the hoe steak, the tuna from the rifle, even the baguette and the chewing gum of pesticides and other chemical substances were peppered.
In the case of tap water, the analyses have brought to light the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak was the most "rich" with 34 determined chemical residues, and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unencumbered.
The final risk of this "pollutant cocktail" to the consumer "is likely to be undervalued," according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed, for its part, "in the face of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase in civilisation diseases."
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) had identified reference to the presence of residues of 365 of various pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in grains.
